Finding the nth term of a quadratic sequence
Here is a sequence:
\big\{10, 21, 36, 55, 78\big\}
Calculate the differences:
\begin{matrix}10, 21, 36, 55, 78 \\ 11, 15, 19, 23\end{matrix}
The difference is not constant so we have an n^2 term. We need to calculate the second difference.
\begin{matrix}10, 21, 36, 55, 78 \\ 11, 15, 19, 23 \\ 2, \space 2, \space 2\end{matrix}
The second difference is 2. Halving this will get us the coefficient of n^2. Since \frac{2}{2} = 1, we have just 1 n^2.
